## Setting Up Burp Suite as a Proxy

Before you can test web applications, you need Burp Suite intercepting your browser traffic. Here is the setup:

1. Open Burp Suite Community Edition (pre-installed on Kali, or download from https://portswigger.net/burp/communitydownload)
2. Go to **Proxy → Intercept** and make sure intercept is turned **off** for now — you want to browse normally but have Burp recording traffic
3. Go to **Proxy → Options** and note the listener address — by default it is `127.0.0.1:8080`
4. In Firefox, go to **Settings → Network Settings → Manual Proxy Configuration** and set HTTP Proxy to `127.0.0.1` port `8080`
5. Install the PortSwigger CA certificate in Firefox so HTTPS traffic is visible — Burp's Proxy Options page explains exactly how

Once this is set up, every request your browser makes passes through Burp. You can see it in the **HTTP History** tab. This view alone — just reading the raw requests and responses — teaches you an enormous amount about how web applications work.

