## Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)

Cross-site scripting happens when an application includes user-supplied data in a web page without properly encoding it, allowing an attacker to inject JavaScript that executes in other users' browsers.

There are three types:

**Reflected XSS** — the malicious script is in the URL or request, and the application reflects it back in the response. The victim must click a crafted link. If you can get `<script>alert(1)</script>` to execute in a page, you have demonstrated reflected XSS.

**Stored XSS** — the malicious script is saved in the application's database (in a comment, profile field, or message) and executes for every user who views that content. This is more dangerous because no crafted link is needed — anyone visiting the page is affected.

**DOM-based XSS** — the vulnerability is in client-side JavaScript that writes user-controlled data to the page unsafely, without the data ever going to the server.

Why does XSS matter? An attacker who can run JavaScript in another user's browser can steal their session cookies (hijacking their account), redirect them to fake login pages, log everything they type, or perform actions as that user on any site they are logged into.

**How to find it:** Look for anywhere user input is reflected in a page — search results, profile pages, comment sections. Enter `<script>alert(1)</script>` and see if it executes or appears as escaped plain text.

**Practice:** https://portswigger.net/web-security/cross-site-scripting

**The fix:** Encode all user-supplied output before including it in HTML. Implement a Content Security Policy header to limit what scripts can execute.

