## Broken Access Control

Access control determines what authenticated users are allowed to do. Broken access control means users can do things they should not — access other users' data, perform admin functions, or escalate privileges.

This is the number one vulnerability on the OWASP Top 10. It is extremely common and often simple to find.

**Insecure Direct Object References (IDOR)** are the most common form. You are logged in as user 1001 and your profile is at `/profile?id=1001`. What happens when you change the URL to `/profile?id=1002`? If you can see or edit another user's profile, that is an IDOR vulnerability.

This pattern appears everywhere — order confirmations with sequential IDs, invoice downloads with predictable filenames, API endpoints that return data based on a parameter without verifying the requester is authorised.

**Horizontal privilege escalation** means accessing resources belonging to another user at the same privilege level. **Vertical privilege escalation** means accessing resources that require higher privileges — for example, accessing admin functionality as a regular user.

**How to find it:** Any time you see an ID, number, or filename in a URL or request parameter, test whether changing it gives you access to something you should not have. Also test whether non-admin users can access admin URLs directly — try `/admin`, `/admin/users`, `/admin/settings`. Many applications hide these links but do not enforce access controls on the actual endpoints.

**Practice:** https://portswigger.net/web-security/access-control

