## Authentication Vulnerabilities

Authentication is how an application verifies who you are. Vulnerabilities here let attackers bypass login or take over accounts.

**No lockout policy** — as demonstrated by Hydra in Chapter 04, applications without account lockout after failed attempts are vulnerable to brute-force. An application should lock or slow logins after a small number of failures.

**Username enumeration** — an application that returns "incorrect password" for a valid username but "user not found" for an invalid one leaks information. An attacker can use this to build a list of valid usernames before attempting to crack passwords.

**Insecure password reset** — password reset flows are a common weak point. Predictable reset tokens, tokens that never expire, links that work even after being used once — all of these have been exploited in real attacks.

**How to find it:** Pay close attention to error messages during login — do they reveal whether the username or password was wrong? Test password reset flows carefully. Check whether session cookies change after login (they should, to prevent session fixation). Use Burp Intruder to test for brute-force protection.

**Practice:** https://portswigger.net/web-security/authentication

